Area Forecast Discussion
National Weather Service San Francisco CA
505 AM PST Wed Jan 3 2024

...New AVIATION, MARINE...

.SYNOPSIS...
Issued at 204 AM PST Wed Jan 3 2024

Showers ending this morning with breezy winds and high surf today.
Unsettled pattern persists into next week with cooler temperatures
and periodic light rain chances.

&&

.SHORT TERM...
(Today and tonight)
Issued at 204 AM PST Wed Jan 3 2024

A meridionally amplified upper trough will progress through the
region today as a cooler airmass spills in behind a surface cold
front. Scattered showers will persist this morning before the better
moisture is scoured out via breezy northerly winds. Look for gusts
in the 20-30 mph range along the coast, within the higher terrain,
and through the valleys. Highs today will be in the mid to upper 50s
within the lower terrain with 40s in the mountains. Clearing skies
should allow lows tonight to dip into the 40s along the coast with
30s for the cooler inland areas.

&&

.LONG TERM...
(Thursday through Tuesday)
Issued at 204 AM PST Wed Jan 3 2024

The upper flow pattern will remain amplified with transitory upper
ridging bringing quieter conditions for Thursday. Light rain chances
return by Friday with a better shot for more widespread wetting
rain this weekend. Colder overnight temperatures should prevail by
early next with with frost and freezing temperatures becoming
more likely away from the immediate coast and bays. Shower chances
look to return towards the middle portion of next week.

&&

.AVIATION...
(12Z TAFS)
Issued at 505 AM PST Wed Jan 3 2024

Scattered showers continue to push through the region this morning,
but are expected to cease into the late morning. Despite the
scattered showers, conditions are VFR with mid level clouds. VFR is
expected to last through the TAF period. Winds today breezy to
moderate out of the W/NW and gusting up to 20 knots in the late
afternoon. Into the nighttime hours, winds ease to become light.


Vicinity of SFO...VFR through the TAF period, with mid level clouds
present. A few showers remain possible this morning, but activity
will continue to decrease into the late morning. Winds will be out
of the NW and will strengthen this afternoon, gusting at around 23
knots. Into morning hours of Thursday, gusts cease, though winds
stay somewhat elevated around 8 knots.

SFO Bridge Approach...Similar to SFO.

Monterey Bay Terminals...VFR through the TAF period. NW winds
strengthen in the afternoon, with gusts up to 22 knots possible at
KSNS. Not expecting to see much in the way of strong g

&&

.MARINE...
(Today through Monday)
Issued at 505 AM PST Wed Jan 3 2024

Radar continues to show shower activity over the water this
morning. However, expect rain activity to diminish into the
daytime as the system pushes out of the region. Southerly winds
remain elevated and gusty through the early morning of Thursday,
thereafter easing to become moderate. Moderate period WNW swell
continues to push through the waters through the week, with a new
and longer period NW swell train entering the waters into the
weekend.

&&

.BEACHES...
Issued at 436 AM PST Tue Jan 2 2024

A High Surf Advisory is in effect from 4 AM Wednesday to 4 AM PST
Thursday. Expect dangerous wave conditions with breaking waves 19
to 23 feet. Large waves can sweep across the beach without
warning, pulling people into the sea from rocks, jetties and
beaches. These large waves can be erratic and unpredictable.

Remain out of the water during the High Surf Advisory to avoid
dangerous swimming conditions. Avoid going out onto rocks and
jetties as large waves can sweep people into the water, and never
turn your back on the ocean!

&&

